Thw word '''Jolly''' can be used as either a noun or an adjective.

*A jolly is an event which is perceived to be more enjoyable than useful, and is perhaps a [[freebie]] too
*A jolly can mean "very", as in a "jolly good show"
*A jolly is a party or celebration.

==Usage==

Usage of the word "jolly" as an adjective is perceived to be [[old fashioned]], conjouring up [[stereotypical]] images of [[crusty]] old [[British India Army]] [[colonel]]s uttering "jolly good show" as they [[pop off]] for [[tiffin]] or an [[snifter]] after the final [[chukka]] of a days [[polo]].

==As a name==

*Jolly is a name that is found in some name books.  It is listed as an "unusual" name and shares the same meaning as the French name, Jolie.  It is derived from the Old French(OFR)word,
"joli" that means "merriness."
*The name is quite popular in Southern India where the French once visited and settled.  It is also used as a result of the British presence.
*Jolly is a unisex name in South India.

==Other usage==

*Jolly is commonly used in those parts of the world where the British have colonized.
*When interviewed, a South Indian man said "jolly" also meant "star" and "innocence."  It isnot clear what was meant by this use.  
*In parts of Jamaica, people use the term in expressions.  
*In [[Chaucer]]'s day, the word expressed different shades of meaning. (See "Joly")
*Jolly or Joly is also a common surname in many parts of the world.

